haking in my hand while im trying to ink? And stances to hold it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uretrotorque.showPublicProfile?language=EN>RetroTorque</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/7/02 2:53:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4150.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.liquid2k.com/solidnate/sig.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Shaking and Pen Stances.</span><hr size=1> What works for me is to support the elbow on my drawing arm. It's difficult to have a steady hand when your elbow is hanging out in space. You hand will also shake less once you put the pen on the paper because the vibration will have somewhere to travel to.<br>
<br>
Although if your inking with a brush I find it easiest to stand intsead of sit and I hold the brush perpindicular to the plane of the paper. Your hand may shake but it doesn't interfere with the brush as much as with a pen. <p>Be well, do good work, and keep in touch. -Writer's Almanac NPR</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ucaptainmeth.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Captain Meth</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Violent Femme</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/7/02 4:10:25 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4150.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.methart.com/t_meth1.jpg  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Shaking and Pen Stances.</span><hr size=1> The only surefire cure for shakiness which I've found, so far, is to ink faster.  It's really bad advice, and it takes a lot of practice, but the faster you ink, the less shakey your lines get.  Practice on some scrap paper for a while before you get the hang of it. <p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
